---
// About / mission. This is the page that carries the project's voice — why it
// exists, who "we" is, and why the scope is deliberately small. Everything here
// must stay true today (same rule as the accessibility statement): no roadmap
// claims written in the present tense.
// On-demand so a visitor's saved accessibility settings apply while they read it.
export const prerender = false;

import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description="Why Access Atlas exists, who builds it, and why it starts in Buffalo and Erie County rather than everywhere."
>
  <h1>About Access Atlas</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    Access Atlas is a directory of accessible places and disabled-led providers in
    Buffalo and Erie County, built by disabled people. It exists because
    “accessible” gets recorded as one fact about a building, when it is really a
    different fact for every person who tries to get in.
  </p>

  <p>
    I learned this in New York. My best friend used a wheelchair, and we would go
    to the same places and get stopped by different things — an elevator out of
    service at the station, one large step at a door, an “accessible” hotel room
    too narrow to turn a chair around in. What stopped me was something else
    again: mold, a flight of stairs, nothing on the menu I could eat. Nearly
    every one of those places called itself accessible, and nearly every one of
    them believed it.
  </p>

  <h2>What goes wrong</h2>
  <p>
    They were answering a question that has no single answer. “Is it accessible?”
    sounds like one question and is actually dozens, and which ones matter depends
    entirely on who is asking — which is why the same building can be genuinely
    accessible to one of us and a closed door to the other, on the same afternoon.
    A rating that collapses all of that into one number is not a simplification.
    It is an answer to a question nobody asked.
  </p>
  <p>
    The second failure compounds the first: the information is almost always
    written by the people who own the building rather than the people who have to
    get into it, so it records intent instead of reality — a ramp that exists but
    is chained shut, a step-free entrance that runs around the back through the
    kitchen. Not lies. Just written from the wrong side of the door, by someone
    who never had to test it.
  </p>

  <h2>A checklist cannot do this on its own</h2>
  <p>
    Every university I have spent real time in has been inaccessible in some way,
    and universities are the easy case. They have budgets, legal obligations, and
    usually an office whose entire job this is. What they mostly do not have is
    anyone who needed the building to work being asked before it was built.
    Standards are worth having — ours are a floor we hold ourselves to — but a
    standard is a minimum someone can satisfy without ever learning what the
    building does to a person. The specifics are where accessibility actually
    lives: the width of that doorway, the height of that counter, the single step
    nobody wrote down.
  </p>
  <p>
    Places do not come out accessible by default. They get that way when someone
    who has the knowledge and the need is in the room while decisions are being
    made, and most places are not built that way — so the checking has to happen
    afterwards, in person, by the people it affects. That is what this site is:
    peer-to-peer verification. Not an authority handing down a rating, but
    disabled people telling each other what they actually found when they got
    there.
  </p>

  <h2>Who “we” is</h2>
  <p>
    Access Atlas is disabled-led. The people deciding what counts as an
    accessibility fact here are people who get stopped by the lack of one. That is
    not a credential we are claiming for marketing purposes — it is the reason the
    labels on this site are shaped the way they are. Every trust label exists
    because someone who needed the information got burned by its absence, and
    wanted to know how much to trust it before making the trip.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Buffalo and Erie County</h2>
  <p>
    New York taught me the problem; Buffalo is where I can do something about it.
    A national directory of unverified listings would be easy to build and worth
    nothing — and the city that generated those stories is exactly the place a
    thin, honest directory would have helped least, because scale is the whole
    difficulty there. Every accessibility claim here has to be confirmed in person
    by someone who was actually there, so coverage can only grow at the speed
    people can walk and roll through it. That argues for starting in one place,
    close to home, where we can check.
  </p>
  <p>
    This means the directory is thin. We would rather it be thin and true. A
    listing that is missing costs you a search somewhere else; a listing that is
    wrong costs you a trip, and sometimes a good deal more than that.
  </p>

  <h2>What we will not do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      We will never reduce accessibility to one star rating. Each fact stands on
      its own, because each person needs different ones.
    </li>
    <li>
      We will never require proof of disability. Owners self-attest; visitors
      contribute pseudonymously. There is no medical gatekeeping here, ever.
    </li>
    <li>
      We will never call self-reported information “verified”. Those are different
      labels and they stay different, even when the directory looks emptier for it.
    </li>
    <li>
      We will never sell your data or load third-party trackers to watch you read.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to check us</h2>
  <p>
    Everything above is checkable, which is the point. Our
    <a href="/about/privacy/">trust labels</a> are defined in public and say exactly
    what each one is worth. Our <a href="/about/accessibility/">accessibility
    statement</a> describes what the site does today, links the evidence for the
    one hard number it cites, and admits what our automated testing misses. The
    code is open.
  </p>

  <div class="disclaimer">
    <p>
      If you know a place in Buffalo or Erie County that belongs here — or one we
      have listed wrong — <a href="/contribute/submit/">tell us</a>. A single
      credible report that somewhere is not accessible freezes the claim while we
      re-check it. We would rather be corrected than trusted.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
